{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\nToday rebar has TWO session resolvers with DIFFERENT precedence chains:\n`session_log._resolve_session_fp` (`CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ID -> REBAR_SESSION_ID ->\nSESSION_ID -> None`) and `transition_close._resolve_session` (`REBAR_SESSION_ID ->\nSESSION_ID -> git HEAD -> \"unknown\"`). The latter OMITS `CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ID`, so in a\nreal Claude Code session the FORCE_CLOSE audit comment falls through to git HEAD — a value\nthat changes every commit and is not a session id. This is a latent bug, and the two must\nconverge onto ONE shared resolver before anything else in the epic builds on session\nresolution.\n\n## What\nIntroduce one shared `resolve_session_id()` helper in a NEW module\n`src/rebar/_commands/session_id.py`, implementing a single **data-driven, ordered** var\nlist so new harness vars are a one-line add:\n\n    _SESSION_ID_VARS = [\"REBAR_SESSION_ID\", \"CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ID\", \"SESSION_ID\"]\n\nPrecedence rationale: the explicit, rebar-owned `REBAR_SESSION_ID` wins first (an\noperator/hook override is authoritative), then the native harness var\n`CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ID`, then the ambient `SESSION_ID`, else `None`.\n\n- **Empty-string handling (DECISION):** a var whose value is empty / whitespace-only is\n  treated as ABSENT (skipped), matching the existing falsy-`or`-chain semantics. Only the\n  first *non-empty* var wins; all-empty / all-absent -> `None`.\n- **Refactor both call sites onto it:**\n  - `session_log._resolve_session_fp()` -> `return resolve_session_id()`. This\n    **intentionally inverts** session_log's current precedence (today `CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ID`\n    before `REBAR_SESSION_ID`; now `REBAR_SESSION_ID` first). Impact is limited to sessions\n    that set BOTH vars (rare); the unified explicit-rebar-first contract is deliberate and is\n    documented in `docs/config.md`.\n  - `transition_close._resolve_session(tracker)` -> `resolve_session_id() or\n    _short_head(tracker) or \"unknown\"`. The shared resolver returns `None` on absence; the\n    git-HEAD / `\"unknown\"` fallback stays LOCAL to this call site (a cosmetic non-empty\n    audit string). This FIXES THE BUG: `CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ID` is now captured at the\n    FORCE_CLOSE audit site.\n- **AC4 scope (DECISION):** \"never returns git HEAD\" constrains the **return value of\n  `resolve_session_id()` ONLY**. The FORCE_CLOSE audit comment MAY still render short HEAD\n  via the documented local cosmetic fallback — that is out of scope for the shared resolver.\n- **Deferred to S5 (c557):** the OSS harness vars `OPENCODE_SESSION_ID` / `CODEX_THREAD_ID`\n  are added to the list by story `privy-eloquent-nauplius`, which owns verifying their\n  canonical names + harness provenance. S1 ships the extensible list with the three vars\n  above only.\n- Update the existing `_resolve_session` unit tests in\n  `tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_completion_gate.py` (~lines 477-504) that call the\n  private helper, so they reflect the delegation (and guard against an ambient\n  `CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ID` by `delenv`-ing it in the fallback cases).\n- The enumerated consumer `tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_session_log_capture.py` is\n  UNAFFECTED by the precedence inversion and needs NO code change: every fingerprinting case\n  sets `CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ID` only after `delenv`-ing `REBAR_SESSION_ID`/`SESSION_ID`, so\n  no assertion depends on which of REBAR vs CLAUDE_CODE wins (they are never both set). It is\n  simply re-run to prove it stays green after the refactor.\n\n## Scope\n- IN: new `src/rebar/_commands/session_id.py` shared helper + ordered list; refactor of the\n  two existing resolvers; unit tests for precedence / empty-string / all-absent + a\n  call-site wiring test proving `transition_close` captures `CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ID` + a\n  no-duplicate-chains source guard test; update of the `test_completion_gate.py` resolver\n  tests and a green re-run of the (unmodified) `test_session_log_capture.py` consumer;\n  rewrite of the existing `docs/config.md` \"Session provenance\" section.\n- OUT: recording the id on claims (S2 / 68ef); `OPENCODE_SESSION_ID`/`CODEX_THREAD_ID` +\n  harness provenance (S5 / c557); reducer / read / hook work (later stories).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `resolve_session_id()` returns the first NON-EMPTY var in order\n      `REBAR_SESSION_ID -> CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ID -> SESSION_ID`, else `None`.\n      Proof: `pytest tests/unit/test_session_id.py -q` (cases assert each var's precedence).\n- [ ] An empty-string / whitespace-only value is skipped (treated as absent).\n      Proof: `pytest tests/unit/test_session_id.py -k empty -q`.\n- [ ] `resolve_session_id()` NEVER returns git HEAD (its var list contains no git call).\n      Proof: `pytest tests/unit/test_session_id.py -k \"all_absent or none\" -q` asserts\n      `None` when all vars are unset (no HEAD value can appear).\n- [ ] `session_log._resolve_session_fp` and `transition_close._resolve_session` BOTH\n      delegate to the shared helper AND the OLD duplicate env-lookup chains are REMOVED.\n      Proof: a source-guard test in `test_session_id.py` reads both source files and asserts\n      each contains `resolve_session_id` AND contains NO `os.environ.get(\"CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ID\"`,\n      `os.environ.get(\"REBAR_SESSION_ID\"`, or `os.environ.get(\"SESSION_ID\"` literal (the only\n      session-var env reads live in `session_id.py`).\n- [ ] FORCE_CLOSE audit captures `CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ID` when set (the bug fix).\n      Proof: `pytest tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_completion_gate.py -k resolve_session -q`\n      includes a case that sets ONLY `CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ID` and asserts\n      `transition_close._resolve_session(tracker)` returns that value (not HEAD).\n- [ ] Existing `_resolve_session` tests updated and green.\n      Proof: `pytest tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_completion_gate.py -k resolve_session -q`.\n- [ ] The unmodified `test_session_log_capture.py` consumer stays green after the refactor.\n      Proof: `pytest tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_session_log_capture.py -q`.\n- [ ] The existing `docs/config.md` \"Session provenance\" section (currently documenting\n      `REBAR_SESSION_ID -> SESSION_ID -> short git HEAD -> \"unknown\"`) is rewritten to the\n      unified ordered contract, ADDING `CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ID` in its correct position and a\n      one-line precedence-inversion note; the stale `SESSION_ID -> short git HEAD` chain (as\n      the resolver contract) no longer appears. Proof: a doc-content assertion in\n      `test_session_id.py` that reads `docs/config.md` and asserts the new ordered list string\n      is present AND the exact stale contract string is absent.\n\n## Depends on\n- (none — foundation story)"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783540032355836001,"uuid":"22c989be-6ee3-48e0-9759-58719cd9221d"}